======================================================================
AVERAGING ARGUMENT VIA c3
======================================================================

At n=6 kappa>=2: c3(T)=8 always
  avg c3(v) = 3*8/6 = 4
  max c3(v) >= 4, so min c3(T\v) <= 4
  From data: c3(T\v)<=4 => GOOD (verified 100%)
  Therefore: good vertex always exists at n=6!

BUT: c3(T\v)=4 can be BAD (2880 cases at n=6)
This means the c3 averaging argument is NOT sufficient.

Re-examination: at n=6 kappa>=2, c3(T\v)=4:
  Good: 4320, Bad: 2880
  Key: at n=5, score (1,2,2,2,3), c3=4 has both b1=0 (120) and b1=1 (120)
  And score (2,2,2,2,2), c3=4 has b1=0 (120) and b1=1 (40)

